{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a1ffae9c-888a-4e62-996e-92eba9ce619d","content":"No repo-specific docs on this topic, so here's the general guidance:\n\nOn macOS, when `createdump` isn't available (common with NativeAOT since it doesn't ship the CoreCLR diagnostics tooling), you can still get crash dumps via the OS:\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — run `ulimit -c unlimited` before launching your app.\n\n2. **Check for macOS crash reports** — the system automatically writes `.crash` log files to:\n   - `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n   - `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n3. **Use `lldb`** to attach or load a core file:\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./MyApp --core /cores/core.<pid>\n   ```\n   macOS writes cores to `/cores/` (the directory must exist and be writable).\n\n4. **If `/cores/` doesn't work**, ensure:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ```\n\n5. **On Apple Silicon**, SIP may block core dumps. You may need to boot into Recovery and run:\n   ```bash\n   csrutil disable    # or selectively: csrutil enable --without debug\n   ```\n\n6. **Alternative: `lldb` live capture** — attach to the running process before it crashes:\n   ```bash\n   lldb -p <pid>\n   # then in lldb: process save-core myapp.core\n   ```\n\nThe `.crash` reports (step 2) are often the quickest path since macOS generates them automatically — they include the stack trace and faulting thread info without any prior setup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d0870fea-c6e1-4b68-9197-c501399a0ec0","outputTokens":394},"id":"db83aed7-3bbc-47e6-85f3-931ac00e65df","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:01:15.063Z","parentId":"18772797-19f3-4f2f-ae55-45cc83d29f51"}
